Norman origin): habitational name from the city of Caen in Calvados, France."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mabel Caen was born about 1145, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of William fitz Robert de Caen. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gruffudd ap Ifor Bach. She died on 3 November 1183, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1145–3 November 1183":"umbes 1145–3. november 1183","1145–1183":"1145–1183","1130–1211":"1130–1211","1176–1270":"1176–1270","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1211":"1211","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","3 November 1183":"3. november 1183","about 1145":"umbes 1145","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dynevor, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Dinefwr, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1145–3 November 1183":"noin 1145–3. marraskuuta 1183","1145–1183":"1145–1183","1130–1211":"1130–1211","1176–1270":"1176–1270","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1211":"1211","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","3 November 1183":"3. marraskuuta 1183","about 1145":"noin 1145","1130":"1130","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","Gloucestersh